\begin_body

\begin_layout Standard
Sono partito dal seguente modello cinematico:
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{align*}
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
dot{x} &= 
\backslash
frac{
\backslash
eta_R cos(
\backslash
theta)}{2}v_R + 
\backslash
frac{
\backslash
eta_L cos(
\backslash
theta)}{2}v_L 
\backslash

\backslash

\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
dot{y} &= 
\backslash
frac{
\backslash
eta_R sin(
\backslash
theta)}{2}v_R + 
\backslash
frac{
\backslash
eta_L sin(
\backslash
theta)}{2}v_L 
\backslash

\backslash

\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
dot{
\backslash
theta} &= 
\backslash
frac{
\backslash
eta_R}{2d}-
\backslash
frac{
\backslash
eta_L}{2d}
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{align*}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

Dove 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta_{R}=1-s_{R}$
\end_inset

 e 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta_{L}=1-s_{L}$
\end_inset

,
 con 
\begin_inset Formula $s_{R}$
\end_inset

 e 
\begin_inset Formula $s_{L}$
\end_inset

 rispettivamente slip del lato destro e del lato sinistro.
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

L'output della feedback linearization,
 in generale restituisce 
\begin_inset Formula $v_{x}\ $
\end_inset

e 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega$
\end_inset

.
 Queste due si possono convertire in input di controllo al modello cinematico tramite le relazioni
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{align*}
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

v_R &= v_x + d
\backslash
omega 
\backslash

\backslash

\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

v_L &= v_x - d
\backslash
omega 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{align*}
\end_layout

\end_inset

Applicata a un robot mobile,
 la feedback linearization è un processo per cui si approssima la cinematica del robot a quella di un punto nello spazio;
 dato un sistema di riferimento fisso,
 le coordinate di questo punto virtuale saranno:
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{align*}
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

x_P &= x + 
\backslash
epsilon cos(
\backslash
theta) 
\backslash

\backslash

\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

y_P &= y + 
\backslash
epsilon sin(
\backslash
theta) 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{align*}
\end_layout

\end_inset

dove 
\begin_inset Formula $\epsilon$
\end_inset

 è un punto lungo l'asse longitudinale del robot.
 Derivando queste equazioni si ottiene
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{align*}
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
dot{x_P} &= 
\backslash
dot{x} - 
\backslash
epsilon 
\backslash
dot{
\backslash
theta} sin(
\backslash
theta) 
\backslash

\backslash

\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
dot{y_P} &= 
\backslash
dot{y} + 
\backslash
epsilon 
\backslash
dot{
\backslash
theta} cos(
\backslash
theta) 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{align*}
\end_layout

\end_inset

A condizione che 
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{align*}
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
dot{x_P} &= v_{x_P} 
\backslash

\backslash

\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
dot{y_P} &= v_{y_P} 
\backslash

\backslash

\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{align*}
\end_layout

\end_inset

Ora,
 è facile vedere come questo sia un modello MIMO composto da due integratori puri.
 Sostituendo il modello cinematico nelle equazioni si ottiene (passaggi algebrici saltati per brevità)
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{align*}
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
dot{x_P} &= 
\backslash
frac{
\backslash
eta_R}{2}(cos(
\backslash
theta) - 
\backslash
frac{
\backslash
epsilon}{d}sin(
\backslash
theta))(v_x + d
\backslash
omega) + 
\backslash
frac{
\backslash
eta_L}{2}(cos(
\backslash
theta) + 
\backslash
frac{
\backslash
epsilon}{d}sin(
\backslash
theta))(v_x - d
\backslash
omega) 
\backslash

\backslash

\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
dot{y_P} &= 
\backslash
frac{
\backslash
eta_R}{2}(
\backslash
frac{
\backslash
epsilon}{d} cos(
\backslash
theta) + sin(
\backslash
theta))(v_x + d
\backslash
omega) + 
\backslash
frac{
\backslash
eta_L}{2}(-
\backslash
frac{
\backslash
epsilon}{d} cos(
\backslash
theta) + sin(
\backslash
theta))(v_x - d
\backslash
omega) 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{align*}
\end_layout

\end_inset

Nel caso della feedback linearization basata su un differential drive vehicle,
 
\begin_inset Formula $v_{x}$
\end_inset

 e 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega$
\end_inset

 sono dati da
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{align*}
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

v_x &= v_{x_P}cos(
\backslash
theta)+v_{y_P}sin(
\backslash
theta) 
\backslash

\backslash

\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
omega &= -
\backslash
frac{1}{
\backslash
epsilon}sin(
\backslash
theta)v_{x_P}+
\backslash
frac{1}{
\backslash
epsilon}cos(
\backslash
theta)v_{y_P}
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{align*}
\end_layout

\end_inset

Sostituendo queste due equazioni dentro il modello cinematico ideale dopo feedback linearization,
 si ottiene:
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{align*}
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
dot{x_P} &= f_{xx}(
\backslash
eta_R,
\backslash
eta_L,
\backslash
theta)v_{x_P} + f_{xy}(
\backslash
eta_R,
\backslash
eta_L,
\backslash
theta)v_{y_P} 
\backslash

\backslash

\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
dot{y_P} &= f_{yx}(
\backslash
eta_R,
\backslash
eta_L,
\backslash
theta)v_{x_P} + f_{yy}(
\backslash
eta_R,
\backslash
eta_L,
\backslash
theta)v_{y_P}
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{align*}
\end_layout

\end_inset

dove si ottengono i seguenti valori
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{align*}
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

f_{xx}(
\backslash
eta_R,
\backslash
eta_L,
\backslash
theta) &= 
\backslash
frac{
\backslash
eta_R}{2}(1-
\backslash
frac{d^2+
\backslash
epsilon^2}{2de}sin(2
\backslash
theta)) + 
\backslash
frac{
\backslash
eta_L}{2}(1+
\backslash
frac{d^2+
\backslash
epsilon^2}{2de}sin(2
\backslash
theta)) 
\backslash

\backslash

\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

f_{xy}(
\backslash
eta_R,
\backslash
eta_L,
\backslash
theta) &= (
\backslash
frac{
\backslash
eta_R}{2} - 
\backslash
frac{
\backslash
eta_L}{2})(
\backslash
frac{d}{
\backslash
epsilon}cos^2(
\backslash
theta)-
\backslash
frac{
\backslash
epsilon}{d}sin^2(
\backslash
theta)) 
\backslash

\backslash

\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

f_{yx}(
\backslash
eta_R,
\backslash
eta_L,
\backslash
theta) &= (
\backslash
frac{
\backslash
eta_R}{2} - 
\backslash
frac{
\backslash
eta_L}{2})(
\backslash
