Sostituendo le espressioni per 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{xx},$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $f_{xy},$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $f_{yx},$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $f_{yy}$
\end_inset

 si ottiene la matrice di disaccoppiamento
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

Nel caso generale 
\begin_inset Formula $d\neq\epsilon$
\end_inset

 i termini di accoppiamento non saranno mai contemporaneamente nulli,
 poiché (ricordando che 
\begin_inset Formula $cos^{2}(\theta)=\frac{1+cos(2\theta)}{2}$
\end_inset

 e 
\begin_inset Formula $sin^{2}(\theta)=\frac{1-cos(2\theta)}{2}$
\end_inset

) si ottiene:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{align*}
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

f_{xy}(
\backslash
eta_R,
\backslash
eta_L,
\backslash
theta) &= 
\backslash
frac{
\backslash
eta_R-
\backslash
eta_L}{4d
\backslash
epsilon}(d^2-
\backslash
epsilon^2+(d^2+
\backslash
epsilon^2)cos(2
\backslash
theta)) 
\backslash

\backslash

\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

f_{yx}(
\backslash
eta_R,
\backslash
eta_L,
\backslash
theta) &= 
\backslash
frac{
\backslash
eta_R-
\backslash
eta_L}{4d
\backslash
epsilon}(
\backslash
epsilon^2-d^2+(d^2+
\backslash
epsilon^2)cos(2
\backslash
theta))
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
